WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:21.000
&gt;&gt; Jane McAuliffe: Good afternoon.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.330
I'm Jane McAuliffe, the
Director of National

00:00:23.330 --> 00:00:26.350
and International Outreach here
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:26.350 --> 00:00:31.670
And I'm delighted to welcome
you to this afternoon's lecture.

00:00:31.670 --> 00:00:34.670
As I make this welcome, I
will also make the request

00:00:34.670 --> 00:00:36.420
that you are now very
used to which is

00:00:36.420 --> 00:00:39.770
to silence your cell phones
before we get started.

00:00:39.770 --> 00:00:43.360
And also to say that we are
filming the lecture today,

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:45.400
and it will be placed
on both the Library

00:00:45.400 --> 00:00:47.920
and the Kluge Center websites.

00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:50.720
Because our lecture
this afternoon is hosted

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:53.800
by the John W. Kluge Center.

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:58.310 position:56%
I like to characterize the Center
of which I was recently the Director

00:00:58.310 --> 00:01:02.590
as the place in the Library
of Congress that supports,

00:01:02.590 --> 00:01:06.170
that showcases, and that
celebrates scholarship.

00:01:06.170 --> 00:01:12.690
We support scholarship by hosting
over 100 senior and junior scholars

00:01:12.690 --> 00:01:16.810
in spacious offices and
carrels right next door here

00:01:16.810 --> 00:01:20.110
over the course of a year.

00:01:20.110 --> 00:01:23.060
We showcase scholarship by
events like this afternoon,

00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:26.420
where we have distinguished
lecturers, sometimes symposia,

00:01:26.420 --> 00:01:30.820
sometimes panels, usually
in this room.

00:01:30.820 --> 00:01:32.970
And we celebrate scholarship

00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:36.910
by awarding every few years
the Kluge Prize for the Study

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:40.050
of Humanity, a Nobel
Prize-level award

00:01:40.050 --> 00:01:43.990
in the humanities and
social sciences.

00:01:43.990 --> 00:01:47.710
Today's lecture is by Dr.
John Sexton and is titled

00:01:47.710 --> 00:01:53.190
"The American Research
University, the Decades Ahead."

00:01:53.190 --> 00:01:55.140
Dr. Sexton notes that for more

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:57.910
than a century the
university has been one

00:01:57.910 --> 00:02:01.990
of America's most durable
institutions.

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:04.110
Yet globalization, technology,

00:02:04.110 --> 00:02:09.770
and market forces are reshaping
the research university's form

00:02:09.770 --> 00:02:11.070
and its functions.

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:14.100
So the question for this
afternoon is what kind

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:19.860
of future can our colleges
and universities anticipate?

00:02:19.860 --> 00:02:23.810
John Sexton is President Emeritus,
the Immediate Past President

00:02:23.810 --> 00:02:27.920
of New York University where he's
also the Benjamin Butler Professor

00:02:27.920 --> 00:02:32.530
of Law and the Dean
Emeritus of NYU's Law School.

00:02:32.530 --> 00:02:38.040
He took a BA, an MA, and a PhD from
Fordham University and then went

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:42.130
on to do some JD magna cum
laude from Harvard University

00:02:42.130 --> 00:02:46.130
that he completed in 1979.

00:02:46.130 --> 00:02:47.540
All through his undergraduate

00:02:47.540 --> 00:02:50.030
and graduate years he
coached the debate team

00:02:50.030 --> 00:02:54.030
at a Catholic girls' school, Saint
Brenden's, in Brooklyn, New York,

00:02:54.030 --> 00:02:57.680
and took them to five
national championships.

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:03.250
After law school John served
as a Supreme Court Law Clerk

00:03:03.250 --> 00:03:06.410
to Justice Warren Burger,
Chief Justice Warren Burger,

00:03:06.410 --> 00:03:11.600
and then joined the NYU
Law Faculty in 1981.

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:15.020
He was named Dean of
the Law School in 1988.

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:19.020
And in 2001 he was named
President of the University,

00:03:19.020 --> 00:03:24.100
a position that he held
until just this past January.

00:03:24.100 --> 00:03:29.010
As President at NYU he led the
University's global expansion,

00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:33.630
opening campuses in
Abu Dhabi and Shanghai.

00:03:33.630 --> 00:03:38.520
He doubled student applications,
he doubled student financial aid,

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:41.980
and grew the endowment
from 1.14 billion

00:03:41.980 --> 00:03:48.060
in 2002 to 3.49 billion in 2014.

00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:50.630
John's been honored
in very many ways.

00:03:50.630 --> 00:03:53.550
He's a Fellow of the American
Academy of Arts and Sciences

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:56.700
and a member of the Council
on Foreign Relations.

00:03:56.700 --> 00:04:02.120
He's the recipient of 17
honorary degrees, and counting.

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:05.000
And he's written and
published widely.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.260
He has a leading case
book on civil procedure.

00:04:08.260 --> 00:04:10.780
He's written on the Supreme Court.

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:14.730
Nice that he spent time here, so
close to the court, once again.

00:04:14.730 --> 00:04:17.280
Entitled <i>Redefining the
Supreme Court's Rule,</i>

00:04:17.280 --> 00:04:21.390
<i>a Theory of Managing the
Federal Court System </i>.

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:26.320
His latest book is entitled
<i>Baseball as a Road to God,</i>

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:27.740
<i>Seeing Beyond the Game </i>.

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:30.430
It was published just
over two years ago

00:04:30.430 --> 00:04:32.910
and became a <i>New York
Times </i>bestseller.

00:04:32.910 --> 00:04:36.410
The book is based on an
undergraduate seminar

00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:40.050
that John teaches each
spring at NYU.

00:04:40.050 --> 00:04:43.040
For the last five months John
has been in residence here

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:45.870
at the Kluge Center
as the Kluge Chair

00:04:45.870 --> 00:04:47.730
in American Law and Governance.

00:04:47.730 --> 00:04:50.310
This is one of the
five chairs articulated

00:04:50.310 --> 00:04:54.620
in the original founding
documents of the Kluge Center.

00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:57.340
During his time here he's been
putting together a book based

00:04:57.340 --> 00:05:02.220
on essays that he wrote during
his years as NYU's President

00:05:02.220 --> 00:05:06.120
about the place and
promise of higher education.

00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:08.940
I can guarantee you
a very stimulating

00:05:08.940 --> 00:05:11.860
and interesting conversation
this afternoon.

00:05:11.860 --> 00:05:13.660
John Sexton.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:20.660
[ Applause ]

00:05:20.660 --> 00:05:22.960
&gt;&gt; John Sexton: Hmm.

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:25.710
Thank you very much, Jane.

00:05:25.710 --> 00:05:29.850
And thank you to each of you
for being here this afternoon.

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:33.210
I see several of my colleagues
from the Kluge Center.

00:05:33.210 --> 00:05:37.470
I know how valuable the time
is, both for the senior scholars

00:05:37.470 --> 00:05:42.540
and for those that are more
junior in their careers.

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:46.590
It's a great honor to me
that you would take time away

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:50.520
from your workshop to come here.

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:54.880
All of us at the Kluge
Center I think echo the words

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:59.520
of the great Jaroslav
Pelikan in our own way.

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:02.720
Pelikan, who was the
first Kluge Professor,

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:06.600
at least in the first class, said
that being the Kluge Professor

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:10.460
at the Library of Congress is like
being a mouse in a cheese factory.

00:06:10.460 --> 00:06:16.180
And in one way or another I think
we've all had that experience.

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:20.060
I want to thank the Library of
Congress and thank the Kluge Center

00:06:20.060 --> 00:06:21.850
and most of all thank Jane

00:06:21.850 --> 00:06:26.970
because Jane is an extraordinary
leader in higher education.

00:06:26.970 --> 00:06:30.800
I came to know her first when
she was still Dean at Georgetown

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:33.200
and then through her time
as President of Bryn Mawr

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:35.860
and her time leading the
Center here and then now

00:06:35.860 --> 00:06:41.350
on to even more important
duties at the Library.

00:06:41.350 --> 00:06:45.590
She's a great friend and
an extraordinary educator.

00:06:45.590 --> 00:06:47.580
And I know I wouldn't be here

00:06:47.580 --> 00:06:51.260
but for her indulgence
of my eccentricities.

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:55.620
Now she knows my eccentricities
as do many at the Library,

00:06:55.620 --> 00:07:00.080
and one of them is that it's
a very rare thing for me

00:07:00.080 --> 00:07:02.460
to be shackled to a podium.

00:07:02.460 --> 00:07:05.830
I think the prophylactic against
my usual behavior is the fact

00:07:05.830 --> 00:07:08.500
that there was no one in the
front row until people realized

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:12.740
that because of the digitization
of this and the stern lecture

00:07:12.740 --> 00:07:17.530 position:56%
that I got about the necessity of
preserving whatever I'm going to say

00:07:17.530 --> 00:07:20.440
for the archives, I
can't leave this space,

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:23.440
so I want you to know you're safe.

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:27.110
But I do mean it.

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:32.720
Thank you for giving me an hour of
your time today, those that stay

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:37.380
for the fullness of our talk and
the Question and Answer after it.

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:43.050
I want to thank especially a
dear friend who in the process

00:07:43.050 --> 00:07:47.010
of being a friend also happened to
become Governor of New York State,

00:07:47.010 --> 00:07:51.620
my friend David Patterson who is
down principally to have dinner

00:07:51.620 --> 00:07:55.690
with me and a mutual friend, but
somehow wandered into the Library

00:07:55.690 --> 00:08:02.150
and decided that he could take as
much as four or five hours with me

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:05.810
since he's got to leave here after
a session with me and go to dinner.

00:08:05.810 --> 00:08:08.750
I want to say this about David.

00:08:08.750 --> 00:08:14.940
In my 14 years as President of
NYU, dealt with four governors

00:08:14.940 --> 00:08:20.230
of our state and -- the other
three were strong personalities

00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:22.710
and in some ways strong governors.

00:08:22.710 --> 00:08:27.800
There was no one of the other
three and very few leaders

00:08:27.800 --> 00:08:32.260
that I've encountered anywhere who
appreciated fully the importance

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:36.150
of education, of higher education,
and of the research university

00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:38.610
in particular the way David did.

00:08:38.610 --> 00:08:41.950
He would frequently point
out that it was in the depths

00:08:41.950 --> 00:08:46.340
of the Civil War that Abraham
Lincoln signed the Morrill Act

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:49.050
and created the Land
Grant University School.

00:08:49.050 --> 00:08:50.410
That's what leadership is about,

00:08:50.410 --> 00:08:54.600
seeing the long run even
in the darkest days.

00:08:54.600 --> 00:08:57.940
And in a way that's what
my talk is about today.

00:08:57.940 --> 00:09:02.540
Now I'm going to start
by covering some ground.

00:09:02.540 --> 00:09:04.510 position:56%
I'll do it in some ways elliptically

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:08.180
because we will reserve some
time at the end for colloquy.

00:09:08.180 --> 00:09:11.520
If you have an irresistible urge,
you can interrupt me at any time.

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:13.750
I'm not adverse to that.

00:09:13.750 --> 00:09:19.370
But the way I planned it, at least,
is I'll talk for about 40 minutes

00:09:19.370 --> 00:09:22.350
and then we'll open
it up for questions.

00:09:22.350 --> 00:09:25.530
I want you to know
as we go into this

00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:31.620
that notwithstanding the very
kind introduction from Jane,

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:34.470
you could not penetrate through
that except if you really played

00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:38.720
out the fact that I spent 15 years
working with high school kids

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:42.060
in Brooklyn in and around
an educational program built

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:43.360
on a debate team.

00:09:43.360 --> 00:09:48.210
You couldn't really begin to
glimpse how eccentric it is for me

00:09:48.210 --> 00:09:51.410
to be here as the Kluge
Professor and to speak to you

00:09:51.410 --> 00:09:56.180
about higher education after the
eccentric way in which I was Dean

00:09:56.180 --> 00:10:00.050 position:56%
of NYU's Law School for 14 years and
President of New York University.

00:10:00.050 --> 00:10:06.400
First of all, never in those 28
years did I lose the essential

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:11.930
definition of professional
self which one faces,

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:14.370
or at least faced before
global entry,

00:10:14.370 --> 00:10:18.810 position:56%
when you had to list your profession
on the card as you returned

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:20.350
to the country or entered
another country.

00:10:20.350 --> 00:10:23.840
And for me it's never been anything
but the simple word "Teacher."

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:27.270
I can't even elevate
it to Professor.

00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:33.360
It seems to me that the
teaching element is the core

00:10:33.360 --> 00:10:37.000
of what I've been professionally.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.130
It was what I was put
on Earth to do.

00:10:39.130 --> 00:10:42.780
So my identity is very much that.

00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:48.500
I was a reluctant Dean and a
reluctant President in both cases.

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:54.130
My son came up with a great phrase
to describe this which carried me

00:10:54.130 --> 00:10:57.930
through 28 years in such positions.

00:10:57.930 --> 00:11:01.570
And he did it, thankfully,
in the very first year.

00:11:01.570 --> 00:11:04.740
We had been invited
by the Tisch Family.

00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:07.840
Now that's a name with
which you conjure at NYU.

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:10.600
And we'd been invited by the
Tisch Family to go to their --

00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:15.210
to the owner's box at a New
York Giant football game.

00:11:15.210 --> 00:11:17.070
And I took my son.

00:11:17.070 --> 00:11:23.330 position:56%
And the other guests in the box were
Barbara Streisand and Dan Rather

00:11:23.330 --> 00:11:25.400
and people of that note, you know.

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:26.760
And it was a good football game.

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:28.510
Jed and I were pretty much locked

00:11:28.510 --> 00:11:31.470
in our seats watching the
game for most of the time.

00:11:31.470 --> 00:11:34.440
And in the car on the
way home he said to me,

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:37.580
"Dad, you're a comma person."

00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:41.640
And I said, "What do you
mean, a comma person?"

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:44.440 position:56%
He said, "Well, didn't you notice
that when people came in at halftime

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:48.530
to pay homage to Mr.
Tisch he would say, 'Oh,

00:11:48.530 --> 00:11:50.580
and you know Barbara Streisand.

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:52.760
Oh, you know Dan Rather.

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:54.370
And you know John Sexton, comma,

00:11:54.370 --> 00:11:58.470
the Dean of NYU Law School
[laughter].'" He said,

00:11:58.470 --> 00:12:00.870
"Your presence had to
be explained to people."

00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:04.840 position:56%
He said, "It wasn't even the case
that my presence had to be explained

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:06.990
because I was the little
Sexton kid, you know.

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:09.030
That once you were
there, I was there."

00:12:09.030 --> 00:12:16.520 position:56%
And that's a very useful concept
and it was easy for me to embrace it

00:12:16.520 --> 00:12:18.000
because you have to understand

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.370
that you are the left-hand
side of the comma.

00:12:21.370 --> 00:12:27.490
That's where you love, that's where
you deal with the transcendent

00:12:27.490 --> 00:12:29.310
and beautiful things in life.

00:12:29.310 --> 00:12:31.630
And that's where you
are as a human being.

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:35.040 position:56%
And then there's the right-hand side
of the comma, and you get all kinds

00:12:35.040 --> 00:12:39.730
of -- you know, I had to tell
the comma person story in French

00:12:39.730 --> 00:12:43.730
when I was inducted
into the Legion of Honor

00:12:43.730 --> 00:12:45.070 position:56%
because I wanted them to understand.

00:12:45.070 --> 00:12:47.800
I knew they weren't
inducting John from Brooklyn

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:50.060
into the Legion of Honor.

00:12:50.060 --> 00:12:53.670
NYU had been in Paris for 40
years and they couldn't induct NYU

00:12:53.670 --> 00:12:56.940
into the Legion of Honor,
so, you know, there I was,

00:12:56.940 --> 00:12:59.370
the French comma person, you know.

00:12:59.370 --> 00:13:02.880
So you get the adulation,
you get the vilification.

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:06.020
I have to say one of the
huge things that's happened

00:13:06.020 --> 00:13:12.190 position:56%
since January 1st is that, you know,
I am now just the left-hand side

00:13:12.190 --> 00:13:14.430
of the comma, and if I
get vilified it will be

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:16.350
because of something I
do, thank you very much,

00:13:16.350 --> 00:13:21.010
not because somebody scrolled
something in a bathroom someplace.

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:24.750
But one can never forget
the privilege,

00:13:24.750 --> 00:13:33.650
the privilege of being asked to
represent a school, a university,

00:13:33.650 --> 00:13:35.610
as a Dean or as a President,

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:38.170
and to carry the right-hand
side of the comma.

00:13:38.170 --> 00:13:42.020
Although throughout my time, and
this is more the eccentricity,

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:46.490
I continue to write, as Jane
indicated, and I continue

00:13:46.490 --> 00:13:49.970
to teach a full faculty
schedule, so in my last year

00:13:49.970 --> 00:13:54.130
as President I taught five
courses, five full courses,

00:13:54.130 --> 00:14:02.900
and did it by myself because that
reminded me what it was about.

00:14:02.900 --> 00:14:07.450 position:56%
And it was also, to just put the
final touch on the eccentricity part

00:14:07.450 --> 00:14:12.710
of this, it was also my practice
not to go on any for-profit boards,

00:14:12.710 --> 00:14:15.350
that I would only go on
boards if they related

00:14:15.350 --> 00:14:18.480
to education, higher education.

00:14:18.480 --> 00:14:21.930
In the one case of the Federal
Reserve Board in New York,

00:14:21.930 --> 00:14:24.010
the connection was not
obvious to me at first,

00:14:24.010 --> 00:14:25.770
but I became convinced
it was important

00:14:25.770 --> 00:14:29.260
to have the education
voice in that conversation.

00:14:29.260 --> 00:14:31.700
And I think it was.

00:14:31.700 --> 00:14:35.080
And I was able to persuade
my friend, Lee Bollinger,

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:39.140
to succeed me as Chairman of the
Federal Reserve Bank in New York.

00:14:39.140 --> 00:14:42.240
And I think that's been
an important post for us

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:44.490
to have for higher education.

00:14:44.490 --> 00:14:49.420
So I come to my conversation
about the University

00:14:49.420 --> 00:14:54.160
and about the vocation
of being a professor,

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:59.970
being part of the University
as if approaching the sacred.

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:01.900
This is important terrain for me.

00:15:01.900 --> 00:15:07.950
This is the terrain
where I began operating.

00:15:07.950 --> 00:15:12.520
It's now 56 years ago since I
walked into my very first classroom

00:15:12.520 --> 00:15:19.820 position:56%
in a formal sense, and it's been
the last 56 years and every semester

00:15:19.820 --> 00:15:23.390 position:56%
since I've never taken a sabbatical.

00:15:23.390 --> 00:15:24.850
So, to the University.

00:15:24.850 --> 00:15:28.810
First of all, some prefatory words.

00:15:28.810 --> 00:15:33.950
There are 85 institutions
in the world today

00:15:33.950 --> 00:15:40.070
that exist today the way they
existed 500 years ago, in form, 85.

00:15:40.070 --> 00:15:44.930
So the British Parliament,
the Vatican,

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:48.510
eight cantons in Switzerland.

00:15:48.510 --> 00:15:50.600
That's 10 of them already
off the table.

00:15:50.600 --> 00:15:54.780
Of the remaining 75,
70 are universities.

00:15:54.780 --> 00:15:56.080
That tells us something.

00:15:56.080 --> 00:15:58.070
That tells us something
about the durability

00:15:58.070 --> 00:16:00.690
of this powerful instrument.

00:16:00.690 --> 00:16:03.560
And, of course, the reason for the
durability is it deals with that

00:16:03.560 --> 00:16:07.110
which makes us human at our core --

00:16:07.110 --> 00:16:13.570
thought and knowledge
and creativity.

00:16:13.570 --> 00:16:21.860 position:56%
What I want to say today is that
this durability is to be celebrated.

00:16:21.860 --> 00:16:23.820
But it's very fragile.

00:16:23.820 --> 00:16:27.520
And particularly fragile
today, I think,

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:36.750
and I fear that we can
see the undermining

00:16:36.750 --> 00:16:40.220
of this extraordinary
institution and the values

00:16:40.220 --> 00:16:45.170
for which it stands
if we're not careful.

00:16:45.170 --> 00:16:48.760
So there's danger.

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:55.110
On the other hand, the maintenance
of the University, I will submit --

00:16:55.110 --> 00:16:57.400
this is the other part
of my argument.

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:06.400 position:56%
The maintenance of the University is
key to any genuine feeling of hope

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:11.070
about the advancement
of mankind, humankind.

00:17:11.070 --> 00:17:17.770
If one narrows it to the
American Research University,

00:17:17.770 --> 00:17:20.280
I think most people would
say -- I certainly --

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:25.600
there was a collectivity of
us in Athens two years ago

00:17:25.600 --> 00:17:26.910
from all parts of the world.

00:17:26.910 --> 00:17:28.910
We had 12 people and we
played a game, you know,

00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:33.670
we each wrote on a piece of paper
how many of the top universities

00:17:33.670 --> 00:17:36.480
in the world were American.

00:17:36.480 --> 00:17:39.630
And there wasn't a
single person at the table

00:17:39.630 --> 00:17:44.140 position:56%
that put the number at less than 40.

00:17:44.140 --> 00:17:50.180 position:56%
And then we played a second
version of the game which was to say

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:56.610
by 2050 how many of
the top 50 universities

00:17:56.610 --> 00:17:57.910
in the world would be American.

00:17:57.910 --> 00:18:02.670
And there wasn't a single person
at the table that put over 25.

00:18:02.670 --> 00:18:06.980
So I think we could say that the
American Research University today

00:18:06.980 --> 00:18:09.760
is in a halcyon time.

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:13.000
I think it's easy in
conversations like this

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:14.480
to miss the broader picture.

00:18:14.480 --> 00:18:16.050
So let me take a moment to note

00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:19.770
that I just used the
number 40/50, you know.

00:18:19.770 --> 00:18:21.940
I'm in double digits here.

00:18:21.940 --> 00:18:24.430
I was the Chairman of the
American Council on Education.

00:18:24.430 --> 00:18:29.730
There are 5000 colleges and
universities in the United States.

00:18:29.730 --> 00:18:34.890
I've actually had two careers
in colleges and universities.

00:18:34.890 --> 00:18:36.830
The latest one was
described by Jane.

00:18:36.830 --> 00:18:39.810
While I was working with
those high school kids I was

00:18:39.810 --> 00:18:41.360
at St. Francis College in Brooklyn.

00:18:41.360 --> 00:18:43.040
I call it the Harvard of Brooklyn

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:45.400
because it's the oldest
college in Brooklyn.

00:18:45.400 --> 00:18:47.900
But it's a college,
it's a teaching college.

00:18:47.900 --> 00:18:50.700
It's for first generation
college kids.

00:18:50.700 --> 00:18:53.170
It's got the lowest tuition
of any private school,

00:18:53.170 --> 00:18:55.560
certainly in New York,
maybe in the nation.

00:18:55.560 --> 00:18:58.180
And it's a glorious place
where I was Chairman

00:18:58.180 --> 00:19:00.160
of the Religion Department.

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:04.760 position:56%
And if you were to ask me, you know,

00:19:04.760 --> 00:19:08.500
so which of these is the superior
institution, I would say that's

00:19:08.500 --> 00:19:11.630
like asking which is
the superior fruit

00:19:11.630 --> 00:19:15.330
between a banana and a tangerine.

00:19:15.330 --> 00:19:17.240
They're two different beings.

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:18.600
Each excellent in its own way.

00:19:18.600 --> 00:19:23.330
And we frequently, in conversations
about the research university,

00:19:23.330 --> 00:19:25.080
because so many of
us come from it --

00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:27.660
certainly so many that are
constituents of this Library come

00:19:27.660 --> 00:19:31.780
from it -- we forget that
American higher education has

00:19:31.780 --> 00:19:34.080
as a core strength the fact

00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:37.800
that it presents itself
as a symphony orchestra.

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:40.910 position:56%
And you can't do the "1812 Overture"
without the percussion section.

00:19:40.910 --> 00:19:44.260 position:56%
And I'm not going to say whether Sr.
Francis is the percussion section

00:19:44.260 --> 00:19:45.620
of NYU is the percussion section.

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:47.160
But it's important to
have good percussionists

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:50.230
and good brass section
and a good string section

00:19:50.230 --> 00:19:51.610
and so forth in any orchestra.

00:19:51.610 --> 00:19:53.700
And we should begin to think

00:19:53.700 --> 00:19:56.750
of American higher
education in that way.

00:19:56.750 --> 00:20:00.040
That will become important for some
of the issues I'll raise later.

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:04.000
Now there's among the 5000,
be sure, there are schools

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:07.210
that I would not speak about
with the pride that I speak

00:20:07.210 --> 00:20:09.940
about Sr. Francis College or NYU.

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:11.990
I mean I'm not saying that all

00:20:11.990 --> 00:20:14.230
of American higher
education is excellent.

00:20:14.230 --> 00:20:16.980
But be careful because
when it's said

00:20:16.980 --> 00:20:19.440
that American higher education
is the best in the world,

00:20:19.440 --> 00:20:22.440
it's usually a much less
remarkable statement.

00:20:22.440 --> 00:20:25.070
It's talking about
a very narrow band.

00:20:25.070 --> 00:20:29.430 position:56%
And it's worth focusing on that band

00:20:29.430 --> 00:20:36.290
because the research university
is the most complex and complete

00:20:36.290 --> 00:20:41.120
and sophisticated version of
tertiary education we've created.

00:20:41.120 --> 00:20:44.970
And it deals with the full
panoply of human activity

00:20:44.970 --> 00:20:46.810
and the advancement of thought.

00:20:46.810 --> 00:20:50.940
But we shouldn't forget the
rest is there, the other.

00:20:50.940 --> 00:20:58.650
Now as the center of
gravity of excellence

00:20:58.650 --> 00:21:02.010
in the research university
shifts in the direction

00:21:02.010 --> 00:21:04.110
that that Athens dinner
suggested it might,

00:21:04.110 --> 00:21:06.620
all kinds of things
will be happening

00:21:06.620 --> 00:21:09.290
to the other sections
of the orchestra.

00:21:09.290 --> 00:21:11.780
And some of the topics we're going
to talk about today are going

00:21:11.780 --> 00:21:14.440
to be playing out differently in
other sections of the orchestra.

00:21:14.440 --> 00:21:22.150
And I don't think any of
this is to be resisted.

00:21:22.150 --> 00:21:27.000
I certainly don't think that
the concentration of excellence

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.510
in research universities in the
United States is to be resisted.

00:21:29.510 --> 00:21:32.030
The knowledge is not
a zero-sum game.

00:21:32.030 --> 00:21:34.230
Indeed, it's a positive-sum game.

00:21:34.230 --> 00:21:37.150
And Americans -- and it strikes
me particularly at this moment

00:21:37.150 --> 00:21:40.270
in our history -- Americans
are extremely focused

00:21:40.270 --> 00:21:44.960
in a very narcissistic way about
various vertical concentrations,

00:21:44.960 --> 00:21:48.880
be it of wealth or other resources.

00:21:48.880 --> 00:21:53.500
We don't talk enough about the
enormous concentration horizontally

00:21:53.500 --> 00:21:55.900
in all of America and
a few other countries,

00:21:55.900 --> 00:21:57.820
vis-à-vis most of the world.

00:21:57.820 --> 00:22:01.910
And in a just world we have to
redress not only the vertical

00:22:01.910 --> 00:22:08.410
but also the horizontal
maldistributions that exist.

00:22:08.410 --> 00:22:11.440
The question really should be,

00:22:11.440 --> 00:22:16.380
does it have to be a zero-sum
game or a negative-sum game?

00:22:16.380 --> 00:22:17.680
I don't think it does.

00:22:17.680 --> 00:22:19.430
I think it could be
a positive-sum game.

00:22:19.430 --> 00:22:23.110
And if that's the case, then
it becomes about quality.

00:22:23.110 --> 00:22:26.170
How do we maintain
quality and access,

00:22:26.170 --> 00:22:28.960
which is talked about
far too little?

00:22:28.960 --> 00:22:35.550
So to me, just to give you the
punchline, a good outcome to all

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:40.540
of this depends upon
some very simple things.

00:22:40.540 --> 00:22:43.210
Two, really.

00:22:43.210 --> 00:22:49.590
The first is that each element
of the orchestra be able

00:22:49.590 --> 00:22:53.590
to articulate clearly and pursue
vigorously what the Jesuits taught

00:22:53.590 --> 00:22:56.930
me to call the Ratio
Studiorum, the Ratio Studiorum.

00:22:56.930 --> 00:22:59.860
What's the purpose of this
particular part of the orchestra?

00:22:59.860 --> 00:23:01.160
What is the purpose of NYU?

00:23:01.160 --> 00:23:03.440
What is the purpose of
St. Francis College?

00:23:03.440 --> 00:23:04.890
What is the purpose
of any institution?

00:23:04.890 --> 00:23:08.280
What's the purpose of this class
as an offering of the school and --

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:11.690
or this department, as
a segment of the school?

00:23:11.690 --> 00:23:16.820
So the Ratio Studiorum, first and
second it -- I think it turns on,

00:23:16.820 --> 00:23:18.780
frankly, the quality of faculty.

00:23:18.780 --> 00:23:21.020
The faculty have to be --

00:23:21.020 --> 00:23:23.930 position:56%
this doesn't seem to be a remarkable
statement, although it's honored

00:23:23.930 --> 00:23:26.700
in the breech -- the faculty
have to be at least as good

00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:28.140
as the best students in the school.

00:23:28.140 --> 00:23:33.570
You know, we know how to
destroy education systems.

00:23:33.570 --> 00:23:36.700
You do what the New York City
Public School System's done

00:23:36.700 --> 00:23:38.420
for the last five years.

00:23:38.420 --> 00:23:41.670
You know, you hire teachers
that have lower SAT scores

00:23:41.670 --> 00:23:43.850 position:56%
than the students you're graduating.

00:23:43.850 --> 00:23:47.430
That's a ticket for failure
because you're hiring

00:23:47.430 --> 00:23:49.570
from the bottom half
of the existing class.

00:23:49.570 --> 00:23:52.460
And how can they teach
the top of the class?

00:23:52.460 --> 00:23:57.460
So what we have to do is get
faculty that are at least as good,

00:23:57.460 --> 00:24:01.640
and that are dedicated to what
they're doing, and see themselves

00:24:01.640 --> 00:24:05.450
as part of the common enterprise
of what a university is.

00:24:05.450 --> 00:24:11.870
Failure to attend to these two
simple things is very easy.

00:24:11.870 --> 00:24:13.780
It's politically palatable.

00:24:13.780 --> 00:24:17.740
But it's corrosive and it's
the real danger that I see.

00:24:17.740 --> 00:24:23.080
So I'm going to talk roughly for
about five or six minutes each

00:24:23.080 --> 00:24:27.300
about three broad trends, and
then tie it into one final point.

00:24:27.300 --> 00:24:29.570 position:56%
And that will be the next 24 minutes

00:24:29.570 --> 00:24:32.560
or so before I open
it up for questions.

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:35.840
And the three broad
trends are the following.

00:24:35.840 --> 00:24:40.510 position:56%
A trend I perceive which is
relevant to the research university,

00:24:40.510 --> 00:24:43.570
for universities and colleges
generally, that has to do

00:24:43.570 --> 00:24:48.260
with civic discourse and
the life of the mind.

00:24:48.260 --> 00:24:50.240
The second is globalization.

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:51.540
The third is technology.

00:24:51.540 --> 00:24:54.330
Those are three extremely
broad trends.

00:24:54.330 --> 00:25:01.120
The fourth topic I want to hit
brings it all together I think

00:25:01.120 --> 00:25:06.740
and essentially it speaks about
both the peril and the promise

00:25:06.740 --> 00:25:11.820
of education as a determinant
of how these trends play out.

00:25:11.820 --> 00:25:16.300
And I think the way we approach
education can either make it turn

00:25:16.300 --> 00:25:21.490
out quite well or quite poorly.

00:25:21.490 --> 00:25:25.780
So let me start with civic
discourse in the life of the mind.

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:30.470
I'm going to move through
this with rapidity.

00:25:30.470 --> 00:25:32.070
I'm going to use phrases

00:25:32.070 --> 00:25:37.940
that I think will capture the
reality certainly one sees today

00:25:37.940 --> 00:25:41.710
in the political and civic
discourse of this country.

00:25:41.710 --> 00:25:49.810
I start off by saying the core and
essence of the university has to be

00:25:49.810 --> 00:25:56.460
that the disciplines that have
been developed over generations,

00:25:56.460 --> 00:26:01.870
working together increasingly,
discovering connections

00:26:01.870 --> 00:26:06.550
between themselves in a
wonderful way, drive a process

00:26:06.550 --> 00:26:11.680
of knowledge inculcation,
knowledge advancement, creativity.

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:16.780
And importantly in the modern
American research university,

00:26:16.780 --> 00:26:21.620
providing soul to the
professions, be it the doctor

00:26:21.620 --> 00:26:24.820
who understands the patient
as well as the disease,

00:26:24.820 --> 00:26:29.060
or the lawyer who is
[inaudible] and Jeffersonian.

00:26:29.060 --> 00:26:34.180 position:56%
Those are the purposes of the
common enterprise of the university.

00:26:34.180 --> 00:26:35.480
And I say common enterprise

00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:39.860 position:56%
because the university merits the
full engagement of its participants.

00:26:39.860 --> 00:26:46.830
And it should embrace and value
different viewpoints as long

00:26:46.830 --> 00:26:50.080
as the viewpoints are backed with
evidence and not simply assertion.

00:26:50.080 --> 00:26:53.880
I say to my students, "You're not
entitled to opinions in my class.

00:26:53.880 --> 00:26:57.620
You're entitled to viewpoints
and viewpoints can be defended

00:26:57.620 --> 00:26:59.860
with argument and evidence."

00:26:59.860 --> 00:27:05.890
But the university has to --
it doesn't have a viewpoint.

00:27:05.890 --> 00:27:09.710
It values a diversity of
backgrounds and viewpoints.

00:27:09.710 --> 00:27:13.160
It's not a political
tool owned by some,

00:27:13.160 --> 00:27:17.060
to be taking positions
on various issues.

00:27:17.060 --> 00:27:20.270
In fact, rarely should a
university, as the university,

00:27:20.270 --> 00:27:26.010
act politically outside the
core of its means, in my view.

00:27:26.010 --> 00:27:27.710
Now I think we're at a time

00:27:27.710 --> 00:27:33.640
when broad societal trends threaten
the maintenance of excellence.

00:27:33.640 --> 00:27:37.210
If you want a full explication
of this, as Jane said,

00:27:37.210 --> 00:27:41.950
I'm collecting various what
I call reflections of that.

00:27:41.950 --> 00:27:46.640
I've written about 10 of them
over my time as President at NYU.

00:27:46.640 --> 00:27:51.610
They're in the nature of pathway
arguments, pastoral letters.

00:27:51.610 --> 00:27:52.940
They're not postcards.

00:27:52.940 --> 00:27:54.640
They're not research papers.

00:27:54.640 --> 00:27:57.210
They tend to be 40/50 pages long.

00:27:57.210 --> 00:27:58.510
They're not footnoted.

00:27:58.510 --> 00:28:01.590
I rarely quote from anyone.

00:28:01.590 --> 00:28:05.590
But I try to make visible
all the parts of my argument.

00:28:05.590 --> 00:28:11.640
And the one that's most relevant
here I wrote in 2005 and I call the

00:28:11.640 --> 00:28:13.480
"Dogmatism and Complexity,

00:28:13.480 --> 00:28:17.090
the Research University
and Civil Discourse."

00:28:17.090 --> 00:28:19.830
And I'm going to read.

00:28:19.830 --> 00:28:24.810
It's one of the few times that
I quote in the reflection.

00:28:24.810 --> 00:28:27.080
I quoted this little book which,

00:28:27.080 --> 00:28:28.880
if you haven't read
it, you should read.

00:28:28.880 --> 00:28:31.650
It's quite remarkable.

00:28:31.650 --> 00:28:36.340
It's even rarer for me to quote
something in a talk like this.

00:28:36.340 --> 00:28:39.880
But this is worth your rearing
just for the shock value of it.

00:28:39.880 --> 00:28:45.410
Keeping in mind that it was written
25 years ago by a man who was

00:28:45.410 --> 00:28:48.760
at that time in his
80s, Albert Hirschman,

00:28:48.760 --> 00:28:51.230
at the Institute of
Advanced Studies.

00:28:51.230 --> 00:28:52.670
In a book called <i>The Rhetoric</i>

00:28:52.670 --> 00:28:57.960
<i>of Reaction </i>he examines three
movements -- the French Revolution,

00:28:57.960 --> 00:29:01.780
the Suffrage Movement,
and the Great Society.

00:29:01.780 --> 00:29:08.520
And he traces the rhetoric
used both by the progressives

00:29:08.520 --> 00:29:11.710
and the reactionary
in each case, and --

00:29:11.710 --> 00:29:16.060
It's interesting that he says at
the top -- just listen to this.

00:29:16.060 --> 00:29:19.270
This is the basic thesis
of the book.

00:29:19.270 --> 00:29:21.790
"The very stability
and proper functioning

00:29:21.790 --> 00:29:25.090
of a well-ordered democratic
society depend

00:29:25.090 --> 00:29:30.380
on its citizen arraying themselves
in a few major, ideally two,

00:29:30.380 --> 00:29:32.560
clearly defined groups
holding different opinions

00:29:32.560 --> 00:29:34.840
on basic policy issues.

00:29:34.840 --> 00:29:37.700
It can easily happen that
these groups become walled off

00:29:37.700 --> 00:29:40.000
from each other.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:42.980
In this sense, democracy
continuously generates its

00:29:42.980 --> 00:29:44.340
own walls.

00:29:44.340 --> 00:29:47.950
As the process feeds upon itself
over time, each group will,

00:29:47.950 --> 00:29:52.170
at some point, ask about the
other in utter puzzlement

00:29:52.170 --> 00:29:55.590
and often with mutual revulsion.

00:29:55.590 --> 00:29:58.780
How did they ever get
to be that way?"

00:29:58.780 --> 00:30:01.090
Now he wrote that in 1991,
ladies and gentlemen.

00:30:01.090 --> 00:30:03.840
And I quoted it because
I was concerned

00:30:03.840 --> 00:30:10.750
after watching the Presidential
Debates in 2004, okay?

00:30:10.750 --> 00:30:14.850
Today in 2016 things
are exponentially worse.

