University College London --

00:49:19.090 --> 00:49:21.120
that at the end of the
first year, the University

00:49:21.120 --> 00:49:27.130
of the People will look at the top
10% of the class for transfer in

00:49:27.130 --> 00:49:29.720
and now you're moving up a ladder.

00:49:29.720 --> 00:49:31.020
Thank you very much.

00:49:31.020 --> 00:49:32.930
Now maybe the first step would
be the St. Francis College

00:49:32.930 --> 00:49:35.180
when we get this thing
going worldwide.

00:49:35.180 --> 00:49:39.660
But use technology and things
like the University of the People,

00:49:39.660 --> 00:49:43.280
things like mooks, as
search engines for talent.

00:49:43.280 --> 00:49:45.570
But then make the ladders
up available.

00:49:45.570 --> 00:49:48.940
That's the way technology
could be used.

00:49:48.940 --> 00:49:52.010
And this brings me to my
fourth and final topic.

00:49:52.010 --> 00:49:54.160
That is this.

00:49:54.160 --> 00:49:58.560
There's peril and promise in
what I see in the decades ahead.

00:49:58.560 --> 00:50:06.440
The peril is that, as we've
seen work out in so many areas,

00:50:06.440 --> 00:50:11.960
that now higher education, formerly
the instrument of opportunity,

00:50:11.960 --> 00:50:17.780
will become the way to lock in a
caste system that is more powerful

00:50:17.780 --> 00:50:22.250
than any caste system ever
created by a religion,

00:50:22.250 --> 00:50:24.970
where we send the children
of the poor, the uninformed,

00:50:24.970 --> 00:50:29.350
the unconnected, to
$10,000 online colleges

00:50:29.350 --> 00:50:33.620
where they neither get the quality
of education that we understand

00:50:33.620 --> 00:50:38.370 position:56%
at some level, the kids at St.
Francis and at NYU and at Georgetown

00:50:38.370 --> 00:50:39.670
and at Harvard are getting.

00:50:39.670 --> 00:50:41.130
You know, we get that.

00:50:41.130 --> 00:50:42.430
You know, there's something
going [inaudible] because that's

00:50:42.430 --> 00:50:43.730
where we want to send our kids.

00:50:43.730 --> 00:50:46.050
You know, I come from a city

00:50:46.050 --> 00:50:52.980
where people pay $35,000
a year for kindergarten.

00:50:52.980 --> 00:50:58.130
And they fight the people that have
all the knowledge and all the money

00:50:58.130 --> 00:51:01.470
and all the connections
to get their kids in.

00:51:01.470 --> 00:51:03.260
What do they know?

00:51:03.260 --> 00:51:05.610
What do they know?

00:51:05.610 --> 00:51:07.740
Okay? It's so simple.

00:51:07.740 --> 00:51:11.460
Just will you do it for your kids?

00:51:11.460 --> 00:51:13.430
And the fear is that, you know,

00:51:13.430 --> 00:51:17.690
in the past the elites would
give a fortune to their kids

00:51:17.690 --> 00:51:20.280
and there was some chance
their kids would squander it.

00:51:20.280 --> 00:51:23.670
But now we're giving kids
of the elite's education

00:51:23.670 --> 00:51:26.060
that others aren't getting and
we're giving them a network

00:51:26.060 --> 00:51:29.210
of relationships that
comes from that education,

00:51:29.210 --> 00:51:31.750
at least if it's not online.

00:51:31.750 --> 00:51:34.600
So what's the answer?

00:51:34.600 --> 00:51:40.250
Well, I think the answer is to push
the quality of our higher education

00:51:40.250 --> 00:51:46.500 position:56%
as far as we can, paying attention
to the issues I've put on the table.

00:51:46.500 --> 00:51:52.300 position:56%
But it's also to make sure that
everybody has access and information

00:51:52.300 --> 00:51:56.540
and the capacity to
climb ladders up.

00:51:56.540 --> 00:52:00.860
So, I would create literally
a worldwide clearinghouse

00:52:00.860 --> 00:52:03.240
of educational opportunity.

00:52:03.240 --> 00:52:05.690
I'm involved now with an effort

00:52:05.690 --> 00:52:09.040
with Former Prime Minister
Gordon Brown to do just that.

00:52:09.040 --> 00:52:12.470
And I think that we will have
the college version of that up

00:52:12.470 --> 00:52:14.980
and running within a year.

00:52:14.980 --> 00:52:20.410
And we intend to try to do it
for all levels of education.

00:52:20.410 --> 00:52:22.790
I think that we then
have to supplant that,

00:52:22.790 --> 00:52:30.250
because you can't expect many of
the kids out there that are as good

00:52:30.250 --> 00:52:34.390 position:56%
as any kids that are in the best
schools anywhere in the world, okay?

00:52:34.390 --> 00:52:37.510
That's the thing I want
you to understand, okay?

00:52:37.510 --> 00:52:42.000
I want you to know, and excuse
me just for giving one example,

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:44.810
because we've run this
experiment with NYU Abu Dhabi,

00:52:44.810 --> 00:52:48.760
where we were sent out with the
ability to find kids that were

00:52:48.760 --> 00:52:50.470
as good as any in the world.

00:52:50.470 --> 00:52:52.710
That was the admission
standard for NYU Abu Dhabi.

00:52:52.710 --> 00:52:55.390
Clearly admissible to
any school in the world.

00:52:55.390 --> 00:52:59.500
Far higher than the admission
standard for NYU New York.

00:52:59.500 --> 00:53:02.840
So we found Moosebah
[assumed spelling].

00:53:02.840 --> 00:53:04.920
Who is Moosebah?

00:53:04.920 --> 00:53:08.320
Moosebah homeschooled himself
grades one through eight

00:53:08.320 --> 00:53:10.790
in tribal village in Ethiopia.

00:53:10.790 --> 00:53:14.120
He walked five days to Addis
Ababa, knocked on the door

00:53:14.120 --> 00:53:16.810
of the International School, and
said, give me any test you want.

00:53:16.810 --> 00:53:18.540
I want to be in your school.

00:53:18.540 --> 00:53:21.480
He got the highest grades
in the entrance exams.

00:53:21.480 --> 00:53:22.900
They gave him a spot
and a scholarship.

00:53:22.900 --> 00:53:25.910
They didn't find out for six
months he was living alone

00:53:25.910 --> 00:53:27.440
as a 13-year-old in the airport.

00:53:27.440 --> 00:53:31.140
And they gave him housing
at that point, and food.

00:53:31.140 --> 00:53:34.050
He graduated at the
top of his class,

00:53:34.050 --> 00:53:36.710
came as part of the first
graduating class to NYU Abu Dhabi.

00:53:36.710 --> 00:53:41.280
Graduated magna cum laude along
with the best kids in the world.

00:53:41.280 --> 00:53:44.040
He was not alone in that
first class of 150 kids

00:53:44.040 --> 00:53:46.220
with that kind of profile.

00:53:46.220 --> 00:53:48.930
Twenty percent of the class
had that kind of profile.

00:53:48.930 --> 00:53:50.940
Those kids could have been wasted.

00:53:50.940 --> 00:53:53.540
What I'm saying is we have
to get out and we have to --

00:53:53.540 --> 00:53:55.580
we won't always have, you know,

00:53:55.580 --> 00:53:57.540
a Sheikh Mohammed bin
Zayed who's willing to pay

00:53:57.540 --> 00:54:00.540 position:56%
for Moosebah's education or
Teyho's [assumed spelling] education

00:54:00.540 --> 00:54:06.150
or the education of the now more
than a hundred kids of that ilk

00:54:06.150 --> 00:54:08.440
that have graduated
from that one school.

00:54:08.440 --> 00:54:10.190
We've got to generalize this.

00:54:10.190 --> 00:54:14.600
And that means we have to have
something like Teacher America,

00:54:14.600 --> 00:54:16.800
except guidance counsellors
for America that have to be

00:54:16.800 --> 00:54:19.540
out there showing kids
how to get through.

00:54:19.540 --> 00:54:21.110
And not just guidance
counsellors for America

00:54:21.110 --> 00:54:24.350
but guidance counsellors
for the world.

00:54:24.350 --> 00:54:27.990
And then the question is,
after the match is made --

00:54:27.990 --> 00:54:31.350
and we have a serious
problem of undermatching

00:54:31.350 --> 00:54:36.060
in the United States --
[inaudible] in the world, okay.

00:54:36.060 --> 00:54:38.880 position:56%
But just focus on the United States.

00:54:38.880 --> 00:54:42.390
Okay. Systematically -- read
Bill Bowen's work on this.

00:54:42.390 --> 00:54:48.170
Systematically, when you control
for everything, kids that come

00:54:48.170 --> 00:54:51.700
from lower socioeconomic groups
go to colleges that are less good

00:54:51.700 --> 00:54:54.430 position:56%
than the colleges they should go to.

00:54:54.430 --> 00:54:55.730
Controlling for everything.

00:54:55.730 --> 00:54:57.690
And when they get to
the less good place,

00:54:57.690 --> 00:55:01.900
when they're matched less
well, they do less well.

00:55:01.900 --> 00:55:04.020
Why? Because they're
not as stimulated.

00:55:04.020 --> 00:55:05.630
They want the support
services, right?

00:55:05.630 --> 00:55:07.440
All that stuff.

00:55:07.440 --> 00:55:09.860
It just flows.

00:55:09.860 --> 00:55:11.160
It's weird.

00:55:11.160 --> 00:55:16.130
It happens in part because you
have political leaders saying go

00:55:16.130 --> 00:55:19.220
to a $10,000 online school.

00:55:19.220 --> 00:55:21.950
So they think only about the price.

00:55:23.340 --> 00:55:26.080
You'd say community
college is going to be free.

00:55:26.080 --> 00:55:27.380
Oh, that's a bargain.

00:55:27.380 --> 00:55:30.450
So you end up going to a community
college in your area instead

00:55:30.450 --> 00:55:32.970
of investigating further.

00:55:32.970 --> 00:55:35.910
Or maybe you do investigate
further and you make it

00:55:35.910 --> 00:55:37.560
into the school you
should make it into.

00:55:37.560 --> 00:55:40.740 position:56%
But then some less good school comes
along, gives you a scholarship,

00:55:40.740 --> 00:55:42.100
and buys you down in a way.

00:55:42.100 --> 00:55:43.910
I mean, the system is perverse.

00:55:43.910 --> 00:55:49.460 position:56%
And it's a system of a lack of
transparency, a lack of information,

00:55:49.460 --> 00:55:52.330
a lack of guidance,
and then, finally,

00:55:52.330 --> 00:55:57.540
a lack of an ability
to pay in the end.

00:55:57.540 --> 00:56:00.780
And that's where we've
got to take seriously --

00:56:00.780 --> 00:56:04.000
we're never going to get back
to the time that I grew up in.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:06.000
And I wouldn't have gone to
college if it hadn't been

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:08.160
for Nelson Rockefeller and his view

00:56:08.160 --> 00:56:11.020
that higher education
was a public good.

00:56:11.020 --> 00:56:14.040
And if you were a smart kid, you
got a regent state scholarship.

00:56:14.040 --> 00:56:17.960
And as long as you went to school
in New York State, it was for free.

00:56:17.960 --> 00:56:19.260
Public or private.

00:56:19.260 --> 00:56:21.580
You found the best school for you.

00:56:21.580 --> 00:56:22.880
For me it was Fordham.

00:56:22.880 --> 00:56:25.000
It was a private school.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:26.870
But my tuition was covered
by my state scholarship

00:56:26.870 --> 00:56:29.030
because higher education
was a public good.

00:56:29.030 --> 00:56:31.440
Ronald Reagan changed that.

00:56:31.440 --> 00:56:33.870
Right now, higher education
gives you this private good.

00:56:33.870 --> 00:56:35.170
You borrow.

00:56:35.170 --> 00:56:36.940
We got to get it back to at
least the quasi-public good.

00:56:36.940 --> 00:56:39.400
That's where I'm trying to go.

00:56:39.400 --> 00:56:41.140
So the pay-as-you-earn program.

00:56:41.140 --> 00:56:44.310
This is not something
I thought up, okay?

00:56:44.310 --> 00:56:45.730
It's done in Australia.

00:56:45.730 --> 00:56:48.290
It's done in the U.K. now.

00:56:48.290 --> 00:56:50.270
Argonne has started it.

00:56:50.270 --> 00:56:53.020
The Brookings Institute
